---
import MainLayout from '../../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import MotuSidebar from '../../../components/MotuSidebar.astro';
const title = "Modeled Analog EQ";
---
<MainLayout title={title}>
  <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
    <div class="w-[250px] flex-shrink-0">
      <MotuSidebar />
    </div>
    <article class="prose max-w-none">
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>Source: <a href="https://motu.com/products/motuaudio/ultralite-mk3/cuemix-fx-overview.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MOTU product page</a></p>

      <p>The Modeled EQ is a 7-band parametric equalizer with filter curves modeled after British analog console EQ circuitry (drawing from the character of Neve and SSL-style shelving). Apply it to any input or output bus in CueMix FX with zero computer CPU usage.</p>

      <h2>Band Layout</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>High-Pass Filter:</strong> removes low-frequency content below the set frequency — essential for cutting rumble and proximity effect on the SM58.</li>
        <li><strong>Low Shelf:</strong> broad boost or cut below a set frequency — useful for managing bass weight.</li>
        <li><strong>3 Parametric Bands:</strong> frequency-selectable, adjustable Q (bandwidth), boost or cut. The workhorse of corrective and creative EQ.</li>
        <li><strong>High Shelf:</strong> broad boost or cut above a set frequency — add "air" to a recording or tame harshness.</li>
        <li><strong>Low-Pass Filter:</strong> removes content above the set frequency — use for darkening a signal or removing high-frequency noise.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>SM58 Vocal Dial-In Starting Point</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Hi-pass filter at <strong>80 Hz</strong> — removes proximity effect buildup and room rumble.</li>
        <li>Parametric band at <strong>300–500 Hz</strong>, −1 to −2 dB — cleans up the "boxy" midrange that dynamic mics can exhibit in close placement.</li>
        <li>Parametric band at <strong>3–5 kHz</strong>, +1 to +2 dB — enhances presence and vocal intelligibility.</li>
        <li>High shelf at <strong>10–12 kHz</strong>, +1 dB — adds subtle air and openness to the top end.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Hydrasynth Line Input Dial-In</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Hi-pass at <strong>30 Hz</strong> — sub protection; synthesizers can output sub-sonic content that wastes headroom.</li>
        <li>Low shelf at <strong>50–100 Hz</strong>, −1 dB — reduces low-end buildup if the mix already has bass coverage.</li>
        <li>High shelf at <strong>10 kHz</strong>, +1 dB — adds air to pad and lead sounds, improving definition in a busy mix.</li>
      </ul>

      <figure>
        <img src="https://cdn-data.motu.com/site/images/cuemix-fx/mix_large.jpg" alt="CueMix FX software interface" />
        <figcaption>The Modeled EQ is accessed in the CueMix FX EQ tab per channel or bus.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </article>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
